ipmon(8)                                                 ipmon(8)



NNAAMMEE
       ipmon - monitors /dev/ipl for logged packets

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       iippmmoonn  [ --aabbDDFFhhnnppssttvvxxXX ] [ --NN <<ddeevviiccee>> ] [ --oo [[NNSSII]] ] [ --OO
       [[NNSSII]] ] [ --PP <<ppiiddffiillee>> ] [ --SS <<ddeevviiccee>> ] [ --ff <<ddeevviiccee>> ] [
       <<ffiilleennaammee>> ]

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       iippmmoonn  opens  //ddeevv//iippll  for  reading and awaits data to be
       saved from the packet filter.  The binary data  read  from
       the  device  is  reprinted in human readable for, however,
       IP#'s are not mapped back  to  hostnames,  nor  are  ports
       mapped back to service names.  The output goes to standard
       output by default or a filename, if given on  the  command
       line.   Should  the  --ss  option be used, output is instead
       sent to ssyyssllooggdd((88)).  Messages sent  via  syslog  have  the
       day, month and year removed from the message, but the time
       (including microseconds), as recorded in the log, is still
       included.

       Messages  generated  by  ipmon consist of whitespace sepa-
       rated fields.  Fields common to all messages are:

       1. The date of packet receipt. This is suppressed when the
       message is sent to syslog.

       2.  The  time  of  packet  receipt.  This  is  in the form
       HH:MM:SS.F, for hours, minutes seconds, and fractions of a
       second (which can be several digits long).

       3.  The name of the interface the packet was processed on,
       e.g., wwee11.

       4. The group and rule number of  the  rule,  e.g.,  @@00::1177.
       These can be viewed with iippffssttaatt --nn.

       5.  The action: pp for passed, bb for blocked, SS for a short
       packet, nn did not match any rules, LL for a log rule.   The
       order of precedence in showing flags is: S, p, b, n, L.  A
       capital PP or BB means that the packet has been  logged  due
       to a global logging setting, not a particular rule.

       6.  The  addresses.   This  is  actually three fields: the
       source address and port (separted by a comma), the -->> sym-
       bol,   and   the   destination  address  and  port.  E.g.:
       220099..5533..1177..2222,,8800 -->> 119988..7733..222200..1177,,11772222.

       7. PPRR followed by the protocol name or  number,  e.g.,  PPRR
       ttccpp.

       8.  lleenn  followed by the header length and total length of
       the packet, e.g., lleenn 2200 4400.

       If the packet is a TCP packet, there will be an additional
       field  starting  with  a hyphen followed by letters corre-
       sponding to any flags that were  set.   See  the  ipf.conf
       manual page for a list of letters and their flags.

       If  the packet is an ICMP packet, there will be two fields
       at the end, the first always being `icmp',  and  the  next
       being the ICMP message and submessage type, separated by a
       slash, e.g., iiccmmpp 33//33 for a port unreachable message.

       In order for iippmmoonn to properly  work,  the  kernel  option
       IIPPFFIILLTTEERR__LLOOGG must be turned on in your kernel.  Please see
       ooppttiioonnss((44)) for more details.

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       --aa     Open all of the device  logfiles  for  reading  log
              entries  from.   All  entries  are displayed to the
              same output 'device' (stderr or syslog).

       --bb     For rules which log the body of a packet,  generate
              hex  output  representing  the packet contents afte
              the headers.

       --DD     Cause ipmon to turn itself into  a  daemon.   Using
              subshells or backgrounding of ipmon is not required
              to turn it into an orphan so  it  can  run  indefi-
              nately.

       --ff <<ddeevviiccee>>
              specify  an  alternative  device/file from which to
              read the log information for normal IP  Filter  log
              records.

       --FF     Flush the current packet log buffer.  The number of
              bytes flushed is displayed, even should the  result
              be zero.

       --nn     IP addresses and port numbers will be mapped, where
              possible, back into hostnames and service names.

       --NN <<ddeevviiccee>>
              Set the logfile to be opened for  reading  NAT  log
              records from to <device>.

       --oo     Specify which log files to actually read data from.
              N - NAT logfile, S - State logfile, I -  normal  IP
              Filter  logfile.   The  --aa  option is equivalent to
              using --oo NNSSII.

       --OO     Specify which log files you do  not  wish  to  read
              from.   This  is  most  sensibly  used with the --aa.
              Letters available as paramters to this are the same
              as for --oo.

       --pp     Cause  the port number in log messages to always be
              printed as a number and never attempt to look it up
              as from _/_e_t_c_/_s_e_r_v_i_c_e_s, etc.

       --PP <<ppiiddffiillee>>
              Write  the  pid of the ipmon process to a file.  By
              default this is _/_/_e_t_c_/_o_p_t_/_i_p_f_/_i_p_m_o_n_._p_i_d  (Solaris),
              _/_v_a_r_/_r_u_n_/_i_p_m_o_n_._p_i_d     (44BSD    or    later)    or
              _/_e_t_c_/_i_p_m_o_n_._p_i_d for all others.

       --ss     Packet information read in  will  be  sent  through
              syslogd  rather  than saved to a file.  The default
              facility when compiled  and  installed  is  llooccaall00.
              The following levels are used:

              LLOOGG__IINNFFOO  -  packets logged using the "log" keyword
              as the action rather than pass or block.

              LLOOGG__NNOOTTIICCEE - packets logged which are also passed

              LLOOGG__WWAARRNNIINNGG - packets logged which are also blocked

              LLOOGG__EERRRR  - packets which have been logged and which
              can be considered "short".

       --SS <<ddeevviiccee>>
              Set the logfile to be opened for reading state  log
              records from to <device>.

       --tt     read  the  input  file/device  in  a manner akin to
              tail(1).

       --vv     show tcp window, ack and sequence fields.

       --xx     show the packet data in hex.

       --XX     show the log header record data in hex.

DDIIAAGGNNOOSSTTIICCSS
       iippmmoonn expects data that it reads to be consistent with how
       it should be saved and will abort if it fails an assertion
       which detects an anomaly in the recorded data.

FFIILLEESS
       /dev/ipl
       /dev/ipnat
       /dev/ipstate
       /etc/services

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       ipl(4), ipf(8), ipfstat(8), ipnat(8)

